{{Main|hypertension}}

'''Benign hypertension''' or '''benign essential hypertension''' are historical terms that are considered misleading<ref name="pmid14175874">{{cite journal |author=McIver C |title=Blood pressure; a consideration of terminology |journal=Can Med Assoc J |volume=91 |issue= |pages=578–80 |date=September 1964 |pmid=14175874 |pmc=1927435}}</ref> as hypertension is never benign, and consequently they have fallen out of use (see [[history of hypertension]]). The terminology persisted in the [[International Classification of Disease]] (ICD9) but is not included in the current ICD10.
<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beckman|first=Kenneth D.|date=March 2014|title=How to document and code for hypertensive diseases in ICD-10|journal=Family Practice Management|volume=21|issue=2|pages=5–9|issn=1531-1929|pmid=24693838}}</ref>

