{{Infobox hospital <!-- Instructions: All fields and invisible comments should be left intact for future editors, even if currently unused. --> <!-- If copying to another article, please copy the entire template. --> <!-- Full template and instructions at: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_hospital --> | Name = Carney Hospital | Org/Group = [[Steward Health Care System]]<!-- optional --> | Image = The Carney Hospital, Dorchester, Massachusetts (87927).jpg | image alt = <!-- optional --> | Caption = | map_type = | latitude = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type --> | longitude = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type --> | Logo = <!-- optional --> | Logo Size = <!-- optional --> | Location = [[Dorchester, Massachusetts|Dorchester]] | Region = Boston<!-- e.g. County or City - NB autolinked --> | State = Massachusetts<!-- optional UK: England, Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland. US: The US State - NB autolinked --> | Country = US<!-- 2 letter code or in full - NB autolinked --> | Coordinates = | HealthCare = Private<!-- UK:NHS. AU/CA: Medicare. ELSE freetext, eg Private --> | Funding = For-profit<!-- Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public --> | Type = Teaching<!-- Community, District, General, District General, Teaching, Specialist --> | Speciality = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (ie not a broad spectrum of specialities) and Type=Specialist/Teaching --> | Standards = <!-- optional if no national standards --> | Emergency = Yes<!-- UK/IR/HK/SG: Yes/No, CA/US: I/II/III/IV/V for Trauma certification level --> | Helipad = Yes<!-- Optional, use Yes, No, or use Template:Airport codes. Only list if verifiable, leave blank if unknown. --> | Affiliation = [[Tufts University School of Medicine]]<!-- 'None' or Medical School and University affiliations (medical or paramedical) --> | Patron = <!-- 'None' or the individual who acts as the hospital patron --> | Network = <!-- optional --> | Beds = 159 | Founded = 1853 | Closed = <!-- optional --> | Website = http://www.carneyhospital.org<!-- 'None' or http URL --> | Wiki-Links = <!-- optional --> }}
'''Carney Hospital''' is a 159-bed<ref>http://www.caritaschristi.org/oth/Page.asp?PageID=OTH000334{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> community [[teaching hospital]] in [[Dorchester, Massachusetts]], affiliated with [[Tufts University School of Medicine]] and [[Tufts Medical Center]]. The hospital had its beginnings in 1863 in [[South Boston]]. It was the first [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] hospital in [[New England]]. Among its first patients were [[American Civil War]] soldiers. In 1892 a Carney Hospital team performed the first [[abdominal surgery]] in [[Boston]].
==History== [[File:Andrew Carney, Founder of Carney Hospital.png|thumb|left|150px|Andrew Carney (1794-1864), founder of the Carney Hospital<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=NCLiulhYAsoC&pg=PA88 Forest Hills Cemetery]. Arcadia Publishing, 2009</ref>]] [[File:Angel of Mercy, Carney Hospital.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Relief of the [[Miraculous Medal]] on the facade of Carney Hospital (2006)]] Carney Hospital was established in 1863 in [[South Boston]] by [[Andrew Carney]] with a $75,000 donation and with Sister Ann Alexis Shorb, Carney's choice for its first administrator and a member of the [[Daughters of Charity of Saint Vincent de Paul|Daughters of Charity of St. Vincent de Paul]]. It was located on the former Hall Jackson Howe estate on Old Harbor Street on [[South Boston|Telegraph Hill]]. The hospital was designed by Boston City Architect Charles Bateman.<ref name="SAMMARCO2000">Sammarco, Anthony Mitchell, [https://books.google.com/books?id=_JriOswcNEQC&printsec=frontcover ''South Boston, Volume 2''], Arcadia Publishing, 2000. Cf. [https://books.google.com/books?id=_JriOswcNEQC&pg=PA83&lpg=PA83&dq=carney+hospital+south+boston&source=bl&ots=fK_gNg8NF1&sig=p2UX0TkLBW5w7wW85Jbav2ozgos&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ltQTVMqmCNDgsAS76IGYAw&ved=0CEEQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=carney%20hospital%20south%20boston&f=false p.83-90, chapter on Carney Hospital]</ref>
The 40-bed hospital was the first [[Catholic]] hospital in [[New England]].<ref name=history1>{{cite web |url=http://www.carneyhospital.org/Carney-Hospital/About-Us-History |title=Yesterday and Today |accessdate=2007-06-23 |work=History |publisher=Caritas Christi Health Care |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140919151915/http://www.carneyhospital.org/Carney-Hospital/About-Us-History |archivedate=2014-09-19 |df= }}</ref> In 1877, the first outpatient department in Boston was established by the hospital in two adjacent houses, followed by the first skin clinic in Boston in 1891.<ref name=history1/> The first abdominal surgery in USA was carried out in the hospital by [[John Homans]] in 1882.<ref name=dorchesterbook>{{cite book |last=Sammarco |first=Anthony Mitchell |title=Dorchester Volume 2 (MA) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nI63nD0FG-gC&pg=PA109&ots=xOPrLIUyHB&dq=%22carney+hospital%22&sig=zE_ihNZ3aORdZgu7JJrez1apNFs#PPA110,M1 |format= |accessdate=2007-06-24 |series=Images of America |date=February 21, 2000 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |location= |isbn=0-7385-0336-3 |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages=109–110 |chapter=Six }}</ref> The same year, the first [[ovariectomy]] in Boston was carried out in Carney by Henry I. Bowditch.<ref name=dorchesterbook/> The first Catholic nursing school in New England was opened in 1892.<ref name=history1/>
In 1920 the hospital introduced its [[medicine|Residency]] training programs. In 1950 the first plastic hip operation in the [[United States]] was performed by Dr. [[W.R. MacAusland]] at Carney Hospital.<ref name=history1/><ref name=dorchesterbook/> In 1953, the hospital moved from South Boston to its present location in [[Dorchester, Massachusetts|Dorchester]]. The hospital became one of the first in USA to establish community health centers in 1973. Next year, Carney Hospital provided the first medical emergency rooftop helistop in Massachusetts.<ref name=history1/> The hospital celebrated 125 years of service in 1988.<ref name=125years>{{cite news |first=Gloria |last=Negri |title=CARNEY HOSPITAL TURNS 125 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BG&p_theme=bg&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADEE66A0E22E39&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work= |publisher=''[[The Boston Globe]]'' |date=May 30, 1988 |accessdate=2007-06-24 }}</ref> After several months of deliberations,<ref name=caritasmerg>{{cite news |first=Alex |last=Pham |title=CARNEY HOSPITAL WILL BE SOLD TO CATHOLIC HEALTH CARE NETWORK|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BG&p_theme=bg&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADDC7507CBDEB1&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work= |publisher=''The Boston Globe'' |date=November 5, 1996 |accessdate=2007-06-24 }}</ref> In 1997 the hospital became a member of the non-profit [[Caritas Christi Health Care]] group, the second largest health care system in New England, and was christened "Caritas Carney Hospital."<ref name=history1/> Caritas Christi has since been purchased by [[Cerberus Capital Management]] and makes up the majority of the [[Steward Health Care System]], the Cerberus affiliate formed by this purchase.
