{{Orphan|date=November 2016}}

'''Urban Metcalf''' (1775- c1820s) was a clothes salesman and asylum patient who was arrested for allegedly attempting to assassinate [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]]. Metcalf went in and out of various asylums for his entire adult life before eventually being permanently committed to [[Bootham Park Hospital|York asylum]] in 1822.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|url=http://fixatedthreat.com/pdfs/Attacks%20on%20the%20British%20Royal%20Family.pdf|format=PDF|title=Attacks on the British Royal Family: The Role of Psychotic Illness|first1=David V. |last1=James |first2=Paul E. |last2=Mullen |first3=Michele T. |last3=Pathé |first4=J. Reid |last4=Meloy |first5=Frank R. |last5=Farnham |first6=Lulu |last6=Preston |first7=Brian |last7=Darnley |year=2008|pages=59&ndash;67|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Psychiatry and the Law|volume=36|access-date=16 November 2016}}</ref> Metcalf reportedly believed that he was King, based on a 'delusional genealogy', and repeatedly tried to enter royal palaces.<ref name=":0" />

While a patient at [[Bethlem Royal Hospital|Bedlam asylum]], Metcalf wrote a pamphlet titled 'The Interior of Bethlem Hospital' and sent a copy to [[Prince Augustus Frederick, Duke of Sussex|Augustus Frederick, Duke of Sussex]], one of the governors. The book complained about the conduct of officials at the asylum and 'fired a train which exploded and dislodged certain persons and practices'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/storyofbethlehem00odon|title=The story of Bethlehem Hospital from its foundation in 1247|last=O'Donoghue|first=Edward Geoffrey|publisher=E.P. Dutton and Company|year=1915|isbn=|location=New York|pages=328|quote=|via=}}</ref><blockquote>"When in his state of derangement, his propensity was to claim as his own property the royal palaces at Windsor, Kew, St James's, Buckingham House, &c; and he would frequently visit them all and take imaginary possession of them, by contriving to get within their entrances."<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SadgAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA164&lpg=PA164&dq=%22urban+metcalf%22&source=bl&ots=WIC4iPX8BH&sig=6FXTpGfJHvVBhbJusDuL_WLB_ac&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjLmKOxqa3QAhXLDsAKHYS-D2wQ6AEIJzAF#v=onepage&q=%22urban%20metcalf%22&f=false|title=Sketches in Bedlam; or Characteristic traits of insanity, as displayed in the cases of one hundred and forty patients of both sexes, now, or recently, confined in New Bethlehem|last=Anon|first=|publisher=Sherwood Jones & Co|year=1824|isbn=|location=London|pages=164–5|quote=|via=Google Books}}</ref> </blockquote>

